<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">40840560</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>19</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>19</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic-Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1555-0273</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>20</Volume><Issue>10</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Oct</Month><Day>01</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of sports physiology and performance</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Individual and Combined Effects of Sodium Bicarbonate and Sodium Citrate Supplementation on High-Intensity Exercise Performance in Highly Trained Female CrossFit Athletes.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1386</StartPage><EndPage>1392</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1386-1392</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1123/ijspp.2024-0190</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study compared the ingestion of a matched dose (0.3&#xa0;g&#xb7;kg-1 BM) of enteric-coated sodium bicarbonate (SB), sodium citrate (SC), and both combined (SBC) on high-intensity exercise performance using a time-to-peak ingestion strategy.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">Ten trained female CrossFit athletes completed four 6-km cycling time trials after consuming either SB, SC, SBC, or a placebo (PLA) in enteric-coated capsules. Blood acid-base balance was measured preingestion, preexercise, and postexercise.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Preexercise blood [HCO3-] was significantly higher in the SB trial compared with the SC (+2.3 [1.8]&#xa0;mmol&#xb7;L-1, P = .003, g = 1.2) and PLA (+6.5 [1.1&#xa0;mmol&#xb7;L-1, P &lt; .0005, g = 2.5) trial. Performance time was faster with SB trials when compared with SC (-11.6 [8.0]&#xa0;s, P = .01), SBC (-17.2 [9.1]&#xa0;s, P = .001), and PLA (-21.5 [14.5]&#xa0;s, P = .007), with no significant difference between SC (mean difference [MD] = 9.9&#xa0;s, P = .94) and SBC (MD = 4.3, P = 1.0) when compared with PLA. Blood lactate concentration was significantly greater in the SB trial compared with the placebo (MD = 2.4 [2.8]&#xa0;mmol&#xb7;L-1, P &lt; .001). Preexercise gastrointestinal symptom scores were higher with SB when compared to PLA (MD = 2.4 [3.2]&#xa0;arbitrary units, P = .04) and SC (MD = 2.2 [2.7], P = .032).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Ingestion of 0.3&#xa0;g&#xb7;kg-1 BM of SB improved extracellular buffering capacity when compared with SC and PLA, allowing exercise performance improvements.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Martin</LastName><ForeName>Robyn A X J</ForeName><Initials>RAXJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Sport and Physical Activity, Edge Hill University, Ormskirk, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Yang</LastName><ForeName>Xiaolin</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>China Institute of Sport and Health Science, Beijing Sport University, Beijing, BJ, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McNaughton</LastName><ForeName>Lars R</ForeName><Initials>LR</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-3743-3171</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Sport and Physical Activity, Edge Hill University, Ormskirk, United Kingdom.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2025</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>21</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United States</Country><MedlineTA>Int J Sports Physiol Perform</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>101276430</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1555-0265</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><ChemicalList><Chemical><RegistryNumber>8MDF5V39QO</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D017693">Sodium Bicarbonate</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>1Q73Q2JULR</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D000077559">Sodium Citrate</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>33X04XA5AT</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D019344">Lactic Acid</NameOfSubstance></Chemical><Chemical><RegistryNumber>0</RegistryNumber><NameOfSubstance UI="D002951">Citrates</NameOfSubstance></Chemical></ChemicalList><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset><CommentsCorrectionsList><CommentsCorrections RefType="ErratumIn"><RefSource>Int J Sports Physiol Perform. 2025 Oct 23;20(12):1772. doi: 10.1123/ijspp.2025-0545.</RefSource><PMID Version="1">41130448</PMID></CommentsCorrections></CommentsCorrectionsList><MeshHeadingList><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D006801" MajorTopicYN="N">Humans</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D017693" MajorTopicYN="Y">Sodium Bicarbonate</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D005260" MajorTopicYN="N">Female</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D000077559" MajorTopicYN="Y">Sodium Citrate</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000008" MajorTopicYN="N">administration &amp; dosage</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D054874" MajorTopicYN="Y">Athletic Performance</DescriptorName><QualifierName UI="Q000502" MajorTopicYN="N">physiology</QualifierName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D055815" MajorTopicYN="N">Young Adult</DescriptorName></MeshHeading><MeshHeading><DescriptorName UI="D019587" MajorTopicYN="Y">Dietary Supplements</DescriptorName><